Frontend Build Guide — Thymeleaf Web Service (No JavaScript)

Scope: A new, separate web-frontend Spring Boot module — server-rendered Thymeleaf pages for all 4 roles (Customer, Restaurant Owner, Delivery Partner, Admin), talking to the backend exclusively through the API Gateway, with zero JavaScript anywhere in the templates.
Realistic timeline: ~2–3 additional days for one developer, even with Copilot generating most of the boilerplate — this is a full role-based UI across ~25+ pages, not a thin demo wrapper. Treat it as its own phase after the 9 backend services are working, not a "Day 7 afternoon" task.
Companion docs: all previous DayN-Copilot-Prompt-Sequence.md files, Database-Schema-Design.md, Online-Food-Delivery-System-Planning-Document.md


Hard constraint to repeat in every prompt below: No JavaScript, no <script> tags, no AJAX/fetch, no JS-dependent CSS framework components (Bootstrap's navbar-toggler, dropdowns, modals — all of those need JS bundle). Every interaction is a classic HTML form (GET/POST) with a full page reload. Copilot will reach for JS out of habit if you don't say this every time.



0. Discovery — do this before generating any frontend code

Prompt 0.1 — Make Copilot read the real project first

Before writing any frontend code, scan this entire multi-module workspace
and build an accurate inventory of what actually exists. Specifically:

1. List every @RestController class across all 9 business services and
   api-gateway, with their full request mappings (method + path).
2. For each endpoint, note: is it public, or does it require a specific
   role (check any @PreAuthorize/@Secured annotations or security config
   you find)?
3. List every request DTO's fields and validation annotations for the
   endpoints that accept a request body (register, login, create
   restaurant, add menu item, checkout, etc.).
4. List every response DTO's fields for the endpoints that return data.
5. Note the JWT claim structure produced by auth-service's JwtUtil
   (which claims it puts in the token: sub, email, role, etc.)

Summarize this as a markdown scratch file (ENDPOINT_INVENTORY.md, not
part of the final deliverable) so you have accurate ground truth before
generating a single frontend template or controller. Do not invent any
endpoint, field, or role restriction that isn't actually present in the
codebase — if something a screen needs doesn't exist yet, list it under
a "Missing / Needs backend change" section instead of guessing.

Review that inventory file yourself before continuing — it's your check that Copilot is building against your real project, not a hallucinated one.


Prompt 0.2 — Prerequisite: admin pending-approval lists

The Admin pages need to list restaurants/partners awaiting approval — nothing currently exposes that.


Add two small admin-only endpoints to the existing backend:

1. In restaurant-service, add GET /api/restaurants/pending to
   RestaurantController -> calls a new RestaurantService method
   getPendingRestaurants() (repository query: findByApprovalStatus
   ("PENDING")) -> returns List<RestaurantResponse>

2. In delivery-service, add GET /api/delivery-partners/pending to
   DeliveryPartnerController -> calls a new
   getPendingPartners() method (repository query already exists:
   adapt findByAvailabilityStatusAndApprovalStatus or add a simpler
   findByApprovalStatus("PENDING")) -> returns List<DeliveryPartnerResponse>

Both should be restricted to the ADMIN role at the Gateway/security-config
level, same as the other admin-only endpoints. Do not change any other
existing files.


1. Module Setup

Prompt 1.1 — Project skeleton

Add a new module "web-frontend" to the existing multi-module Maven
project (Java 21, Spring Boot 3.2.x, Spring Cloud 2023.0.x). Generate:

1. pom.xml with dependencies: spring-boot-starter-thymeleaf,
   spring-boot-starter-web, spring-boot-starter-security,
   spring-boot-starter-validation, thymeleaf-extras-springsecurity6,
   spring-cloud-starter-openfeign, spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client,
   lombok
2. WebFrontendApplication.java with @EnableFeignClients
3. application.yml:
   - spring.application.name: web-frontend
   - server.port: 8090
   - registers with Eureka at http://localhost:8761/eureka
   - pulls config from Config Server at http://localhost:8888
   - the shared Feign timeout block used across the other services

This module renders HTML — it has no database and no JPA dependency.
This entire module must never use JavaScript. Every page is
server-rendered Thymeleaf, every interaction is a plain HTML form with a
full page reload. Do not add any <script> tag or JS library at any point
in this build.


2. Backend Integration Layer

Prompt 2.1 — Feign clients to the API Gateway

In web-frontend, generate OpenFeign clients that call the API Gateway
(not individual services directly) — package com.fooddelivery.web.client,
one interface per backend service area, all using
@FeignClient(name = "api-gateway"):

- AuthApiClient: POST /api/auth/register, POST /api/auth/login
- CustomerApiClient: POST /api/customers, GET /api/customers/me,
  PUT /api/customers/me, POST/GET /api/customers/me/addresses,
  PUT/DELETE /api/customers/me/addresses/{id}
- RestaurantApiClient: POST /api/restaurants, GET /api/restaurants,
  GET /api/restaurants/pending, GET /api/restaurants/{id},
  PUT /api/restaurants/{id}, PUT /api/restaurants/{id}/open-status
- MenuApiClient: GET /api/restaurants/{restaurantId}/menu,
  POST /api/restaurants/{restaurantId}/categories,
  POST /api/restaurants/{restaurantId}/items,
  PUT /api/items/{itemId}, DELETE /api/items/{itemId}
- OrderApiClient: POST /api/cart/items, GET /api/cart,
  PUT /api/cart/items/{id}, DELETE /api/cart/items/{id},
  POST /api/cart/checkout, GET /api/orders/{id}, GET /api/orders,
  PUT /api/orders/{id}/status, POST /api/orders/{id}/payment,
  GET /api/orders/{id}/payments
- DeliveryApiClient: POST /api/delivery-partners,
  PUT /api/delivery-partners/me/availability,
  PUT /api/delivery-partners/me/location, GET /api/deliveries/{id},
  PUT /api/deliveries/{id}/status
- ReviewApiClient: POST /api/reviews, GET /api/reviews/restaurant/{id},
  GET /api/reviews/customer/me
- NotificationApiClient: GET /api/notifications/me
- AdminApiClient: PUT /api/admin/restaurants/{id}/approval,
  PUT /api/admin/delivery-partners/{id}/approval,
  PUT /api/admin/users/{id}/disable, PUT /api/admin/users/{id}/enable,
  GET /api/admin/audit-logs, GET/PUT /api/admin/settings/{key}

Reuse the exact request/response DTO shapes documented in
ENDPOINT_INVENTORY.md for each call — do not invent extra fields.
Put each client's request/response DTOs in a matching dto subpackage.

Prompt 2.2 — JWT bridging (Feign interceptor)

In web-frontend, generate a FeignAuthInterceptor implementing
RequestInterceptor (com.fooddelivery.web.config) that:

- Reads the current Authentication from SecurityContextHolder
- If the principal is an instance of a custom AuthenticatedUser class
  (created in the next prompt) holding a JWT string, adds header
  "Authorization: Bearer <token>" to every outgoing Feign request
- If there's no authenticated user (e.g. the register/login calls
  themselves), adds no Authorization header

Register this as a @Bean so it applies to every Feign client in this
module automatically.

Prompt 2.3 — Custom authentication

In web-frontend, generate:

1. AuthenticatedUser (com.fooddelivery.web.security) implementing
   Spring Security's UserDetails or usable as a custom principal —
   holds: userId (Long), email, role (String), jwtToken (String)

2. FoodDeliveryAuthenticationProvider implementing AuthenticationProvider:
   - authenticate(Authentication auth) extracts email/password from the
     incoming UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken
   - calls AuthApiClient.login(new LoginRequest(email, password))
   - on success, builds a new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken whose
     principal is an AuthenticatedUser (populated from the AuthResponse
     — decode the JWT's role claim, or use AuthResponse.getRole() if
     already present) and whose authorities is a single
     SimpleGrantedAuthority("ROLE_" + role)
   - on failure (Feign throws a 401/other error), throws
     BadCredentialsException so Spring Security shows the standard
     "invalid login" flow

3. SecurityConfig (@Configuration, @EnableWebSecurity):
   - Registers FoodDeliveryAuthenticationProvider
   - authorizeHttpRequests:
     permitAll: "/", "/login", "/register/**", "/restaurants/**",
                "/css/**", "/error"
     hasRole("CUSTOMER"): "/customer/**"
     hasRole("RESTAURANT_OWNER"): "/restaurant-owner/**"
     hasRole("DELIVERY_PARTNER"): "/delivery/**"
     hasRole("ADMIN"): "/admin/**"
     anyRequest authenticated
   - formLogin: custom login page at "/login", usernameParameter="email",
     defaultSuccessUrl handled by a custom AuthenticationSuccessHandler
     (next bullet) since the post-login redirect depends on role
   - logout: default logout at "/logout", invalidates the session
   - CSRF stays enabled (default) — Thymeleaf's th:action forms pick up
     the CSRF token automatically via thymeleaf-extras-springsecurity6,
     no manual handling needed

4. RoleBasedRedirectHandler implementing
   AuthenticationSuccessHandler: redirects to /customer/dashboard,
   /restaurant-owner/dashboard, /delivery/dashboard, or /admin/dashboard
   based on the authenticated user's role.


3. Shared Layout

Prompt 3.1 — Layout fragments and styling

In web-frontend, generate a shared Thymeleaf layout used by every page:

1. templates/fragments/layout.html containing a reusable HTML skeleton
   (head with a single stylesheet link, header, main content slot via
   th:replace/th:insert, footer) — use Thymeleaf's layout dialect or
   plain th:replace fragments, whichever needs no extra dependency
   beyond what's already added.

2. templates/fragments/nav.html: a navigation bar that uses
   sec:authorize="hasRole('CUSTOMER')" etc. (from
   thymeleaf-extras-springsecurity6) to show only the links relevant to
   the logged-in user's role, plus a plain <form> logout button
   (POST to /logout) when authenticated, and Login/Register links when
   not. No dropdown menus, no collapsible mobile nav (both usually need
   JS) — use a simple horizontal list of links that wraps naturally on
   small screens via CSS flex-wrap.

3. static/css/style.css: a clean, professional, mobile-responsive
   stylesheet using plain CSS (Flexbox/Grid, media queries) — no
   framework, no JS-dependent components. Define a simple, consistent
   color palette (one primary color, one accent, neutral
   grays/whites), consistent spacing scale, card-style containers for
   restaurant/menu-item/order listings, and clear form styling
   (labels, inputs, validation error text in a distinct color).

Do not include Bootstrap, Tailwind's JS plugins, or any CDN <script>
tag. Plain CSS only.

Prompt 3.2 — Global error handling (no JS)

In web-frontend, generate:

1. A GlobalControllerAdvice (@ControllerAdvice) that catches
   FeignException (from any backend call failing) and adds a generic
   flash-friendly error model attribute, so any page can display
   "Something went wrong, please try again" without a stack trace
   leaking to the user.

2. A custom error page (templates/error.html) for 404/500, styled with
   the same layout/stylesheet as the rest of the app.

3. A pattern for form re-display on validation failure: when a POST
   fails Bean Validation, the controller returns the same template name
   with the BindingResult in the model, and the template shows
   th:errors next to each field — no redirect, no JS, just a re-rendered
   page with the user's previously entered values preserved via
   th:field binding.

Use this exact pattern in every form controller generated in the
sections below — state that explicitly so it stays consistent across
all ~20 form-handling controllers in this app.


4. Public Pages (no login required)

Prompt 4.1 — Home, browse, registration, login

In web-frontend, generate:

1. HomeController: GET / -> a simple landing page (templates/home.html)
   with a short description and links to Register/Login/Browse
   Restaurants

2. PublicRestaurantController (package com.fooddelivery.web.controller):
   GET /restaurants?city=      -> calls RestaurantApiClient.search(city),
                                    renders templates/restaurants/list.html
                                    (card grid, each linking to detail)
   GET /restaurants/{id}       -> calls RestaurantApiClient.getById +
                                    MenuApiClient.getMenu, renders
                                    templates/restaurants/detail.html
                                    showing categories/items and a
                                    "reviews" section
                                    (ReviewApiClient.getForRestaurant)

3. RegistrationController:
   GET  /register            -> role selection page
                                 (templates/auth/register-select.html):
                                 links to /register/customer,
                                 /register/restaurant-owner,
                                 /register/delivery-partner (NOT admin —
                                 admin accounts aren't self-service)
   GET  /register/{role}     -> the actual registration form for that
                                 role (templates/auth/register-form.html,
                                 reused with a role parameter)
   POST /register/{role}     -> calls AuthApiClient.register(...) with
                                 the fixed role value baked in server-side
                                 (never trust a hidden form field for
                                 role); on success, redirect to /login
                                 with a flash success message; on
                                 validation failure, re-render the form
                                 with errors per the pattern from
                                 Prompt 3.2

4. LoginController: GET /login -> templates/auth/login.html (a plain
   email+password form posting to Spring Security's default
   "/login" processing URL — no custom POST handler needed since
   SecurityConfig's formLogin handles it)


5. Customer Pages

Prompt 5.1 — Profile completion + address management

In web-frontend, generate a CustomerProfileController
(package com.fooddelivery.web.controller.customer, all mapped under
/customer/**, all requiring the authenticated user):

GET  /customer/dashboard        -> if no customer profile exists yet
                                    (CustomerApiClient.getMe() returns
                                    404), redirect to
                                    /customer/complete-profile; otherwise
                                    show a simple dashboard linking to
                                    Browse Restaurants, My Orders,
                                    My Addresses, My Reviews
GET  /customer/complete-profile -> form to create the profile
POST /customer/complete-profile -> calls CustomerApiClient.create(...)
                                    using the logged-in user's userId
                                    from AuthenticatedUser, then redirect
                                    to /customer/dashboard
GET  /customer/addresses        -> list addresses
GET  /customer/addresses/new    -> add-address form
POST /customer/addresses/new    -> create address, redirect back to list
GET  /customer/addresses/{id}/edit -> edit form
POST /customer/addresses/{id}/edit -> update, redirect back to list
POST /customer/addresses/{id}/delete -> delete, redirect back to list
  (a plain form with a Delete button — no JS confirm dialog; if you want
  a confirmation step, render a separate "Are you sure?" page instead)

Use the form re-display-on-error pattern from Prompt 3.2 throughout.

Prompt 5.2 — Cart and checkout

In web-frontend, generate a CartController
(package com.fooddelivery.web.controller.customer, under /customer/cart):

GET  /customer/cart                    -> OrderApiClient.getCart(),
                                            render templates/customer/cart.html
                                            (item list, quantity update
                                            forms, remove forms, subtotal,
                                            a Checkout button)
POST /customer/cart/items/{id}/update  -> quantity update form, redirect
                                            back to /customer/cart
POST /customer/cart/items/{id}/remove  -> remove form, redirect back
GET  /customer/checkout                -> shows a delivery-address
                                            picker (radio buttons from
                                            CustomerApiClient.getAddresses())
                                            and a payment method choice
                                            (ONLINE/COD radio buttons)
POST /customer/checkout                -> calls OrderApiClient.checkout(...),
                                            redirect to
                                            /customer/orders/{newOrderId}

Also generate a small "add to cart" form embedded directly on the
restaurant detail page (templates/restaurants/detail.html, extend the
one from Prompt 4.1): each menu item has its own small POST form (item
id as a hidden field, quantity as a number input) posting to
POST /customer/cart/items -> calls OrderApiClient.addItem(...), redirects
back to the same restaurant detail page. This requires the customer to
be logged in — if not, redirect to /login first (Spring Security handles
this automatically via the /customer/** role restriction).

Prompt 5.3 — Orders, payment, reviews, notifications

In web-frontend, generate:

1. CustomerOrderController (/customer/orders):
   GET /customer/orders          -> list own orders
                                     (OrderApiClient.getMyOrders())
   GET /customer/orders/{id}     -> order detail: items, status,
                                     total, a "Pay Now" form if
                                     paymentStatus is PENDING and
                                     paymentMethod is ONLINE, and a
                                     "Leave a Review" link if
                                     orderStatus is DELIVERED and no
                                     review exists yet for this order
   POST /customer/orders/{id}/pay -> calls OrderApiClient.recordPayment
                                      (simulated — a simple form with a
                                      "Simulate Successful Payment"
                                      button and a "Simulate Failed
                                      Payment" button, each posting a
                                      fixed status value), redirect back
                                      to the order detail page

2. CustomerReviewController (/customer/reviews):
   GET  /customer/orders/{orderId}/review -> review form (rating radio
                                              1-5, comment textarea)
   POST /customer/orders/{orderId}/review -> calls
                                              ReviewApiClient.submit(...),
                                              redirect to order detail
   GET  /customer/reviews                 -> list of the customer's
                                              submitted reviews

3. CustomerNotificationController (/customer/notifications):
   GET /customer/notifications -> list notifications
                                   (NotificationApiClient.getMine())


